@node Examples,  , Denoting Space Groups, Top
@appendix 40 Example Input Files



The next several pages have numerous examples of @code{atoms.inp} files
that produce the correct output. In these examples you might find a
material of interest or its isomorph and you will certainly get clues
for making @sc{atoms} work the way you want. By far the most useful
resource for the crystallographic data needed for these input files is
the @i{Crystal Structures} series by R.W.G. Wyckoff.

These examples and many others are available on the Internet. The
World wide Web URL for a big list of input files is
@uref{http://krazy.phys.washington.edu/html/atoms.html}.
@c The FTP
@c address is @code{krazy.phys.washington.edu}. Log in as anonymous and
@c give your e-mail address as a password. The example input files are
@c in the directory @code{/pub/Tools/Atoms/}. Please feel free to
@c contribute new input files that you have used. Upload them by FTP to
@c the directory @code{/pub/Incoming/}.


